'''Michael Amir Murillo Bermúdez''' (born 11 February 1996) is a Panamanian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[right-back]] for [[Süper Lig]] club [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]] and the [[Panama national football team|Panama national team]].

==Club career==
===San Francisco===
Born in [[Panama City]], Murillo graduated from [[San Francisco F.C.|San Francisco]]'s youth setup, and made his senior debut in the 2014–15 campaign, aged only 18. He quickly established himself as a first team regular and had his best season in 2015–16 in which he made 21 league appearances and scored 3 goals. On 25 October 2015, Murillo scored his first two goals for ''Los Monjes'' in a 2–1 victory over [[Alianza F.C. (Panama)|Alianza]].<ref name="soccerway">{{cite web|title=SAN FRANCISCO VS. ALIANZA 2–1|url=http://www.es.soccerway.com/matches/2015/10/25/panama/lpf/san-francisco-fc/alianza-fc/2075435/|website=soccerway.com|access-date=25 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520032403/http://es.soccerway.com/matches/2015/10/25/panama/lpf/san-francisco-fc/alianza-fc/2075435/|archive-date=20 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 10 December 2015, Murillo played the entire match for San Francisco in the first edition of the [[Copa Panamá]], as his side won the final against [[Chepo F.C.|Chepo]] 5–4 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]], as the match finished 0–0 after [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]], to win their first title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bitacoradeportiva.com/2015/12/monjes-hacen-historia/|title=Monjes hacen historia|date=11 December 2015|publisher=Bitacora Deportiva|access-date=20 December 2015}}</ref> On 26 August 2015, Murillo helped San Francisco to a famous 2–1 victory over Mexican side [[Querétaro FC]] in a [[2015–16 CONCACAF Champions League]] match.<ref name="laestrella">{{cite web|title=San Francisco gana 2–1 a Querétaro de México en Liga de Campeones|url=http://www.laestrella.com.pa/deportes/futbol/francisco-gana-2-1-queretaro-mexico-liga-campeones/23888037|website=laestrella.com.pa|access-date=26 August 2015}}</ref>

===New York Red Bulls===
On 18 February 2017, it was announced that Murillo was joining [[New York Red Bulls]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2017/02/18/new-york-red-bulls-complete-loan-panama-international-michael-amir-murillo|title=New York Red Bulls Complete Loan of Panama International Michael Amir Murillo|publisher=newyorkredbulls.com|access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref> On 29 July 2017, he scored his first goal for New York in a 4–0 rout over [[Montreal Impact (MLS)|Montreal Impact]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2017/07/29/match-recap-red-bulls-roll-harrison-4-0|title=Red Bulls Roll in Harrison, 4–0|publisher=newyorkredbulls.com|access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref>
On 22 October 2017 Murillo scored his second goal for New York in a 2–1 victory over rival [[D.C. United]], in the last match played at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2017/10/22/match-recap-red-bulls-spoil-party-rfk-finale|title= Red Bulls Spoil The Party at RFK Finale|publisher=newyorkredbulls.com|access-date=22 October 2017}}</ref> The Red Bulls exercised their contract option to permanently sign him on 11 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/27/red-bulls-exercise-loan-option-defender-michael-amir-murillo|title= Red Bulls Exercise loan option on Murillo|publisher=mlssoccer.com|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>

On 13 March 2018, Murillo assisted on two goals in New York's 3–1 victory over [[Club Tijuana]] in the [[CONCACAF Champions League]], helping the club advance to semifinals of the Champions League for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/03/13/post-match-notes-red-bulls-moving-sccl-semis-defeat-tijuana-3-1|title=Red Bulls Moving On to SCCL Semis, Defeat Tijuana, 3–1|date=13 March 2018|work=newyorkredbulls.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref> On 14 April 2018, he scored his first goal of the season for New York in a 3–1 victory over Montreal Impact.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/04/14/match-recap-pres-provident-bank-new-york-red-bulls-bounce-montreal-impact-3-1|title=New York Red Bulls Bounce Montreal Impact, 3–1|date=14 April 2018|work=newyorkredbulls.com|language=en|access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref> He was also selected to participate for the New York Red Bulls in the [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] [[Major League Soccer All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] against Italy's [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] on 1 August 2018 in the [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in Atlanta, Georgia, US, making him the first Panamanian to participate in an [[MLS All-Star Game|MLS All-Star game]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvmax-9.com/somoslasele/Panameno-Michael-Murillo-Juventus-Italia_0_5064993544.html|title=TV Max: Panameño Michael Murillo se las verá con la Juventus de Italia}}</ref>

During his time with the Red Bulls, Murillo totalled 80 appearances in all competitions, scoring four goals and providing eight assists and winning the 2018 Supporters Shield with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/4007166/red-bulls-sell-star-defender-michael-murillo-to-anderlecht|title=Red Bulls sell star defender Michael Murillo to Anderlecht|website=ESPN|date=6 December 2019|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>

===Anderlecht===
On 6 December 2019, the Red Bulls announced the transfer of Murillo to Belgian side [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2019/12/06/new-york-red-bulls-transfer-michael-amir-murillo-rsc-anderlecht|title=New York Red Bulls Transfer Michael Amir Murillo to RSC Anderlecht|date=6 December 2019|website=newyorkredbulls.com|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Murillo scored his first goal for his new club on 23 February 2020, during a 6–1 victory versus [[K.A.S. Eupen|Eupen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2020/02/23/belgium/pro-league/royal-sporting-club-anderlecht/koninklijke-as-eupen/3050357/|title=ANDERLECHT VS. AS EUPEN 6–1|website=soccerway.com|access-date=27 March 2022}}</ref>

===Marseille===
On 30 August 2023, Murillo joined French side [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.om.fr/fr/actualites/4808/club/79069-amir-murillo-est-olympien|title=Amir Murillo est Olympien !|trans-title=Amir Murillo is an Olympian!|language=fr|publisher=Olympique de Marseille|date=30 August 2023|access-date=30 August 2023}}</ref>

===Beşiktaş===
On 6 February 2026, Murillo joined [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]] on a three-and-a-half-year deal with an option for another year for a reported fee of €5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.om.fr/en/news/4803/1st-team/107282-amir-murillo-transferred-besiktas/|title=Amir Murillo has been transferred to Turkish club Besiktas JK.|publisher=[[Olympique de Marseille]]|date=6 February 2026|access-date=6 February 2026|language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Concacaf Gold Cup (48248640306) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Murillo with [[Panama national football team|Panama]] at the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]]]
Murillo was called up for the [[Panama national football team|Panama]] national team, making his debut in 2016. On 27 April 2016, Murillo scored his first goal with Panama in a 2–1 victory over Martinique.<ref name="fepafut">{{cite web|title=Con goles de Michael Murillo y José Batista, Panamá vence 0–2 a Martinica|url=http://www.fepafut.com/single-post/2016/04/27/Con-goles-de-Michael-Murillo-y-Jos%C3%A9-Batista-Panam%C3%A1-vence-02-a-Martinica|website=fepafut.com|access-date=27 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206103709/http://www.fepafut.com/single-post/2016/04/27/Con-goles-de-Michael-Murillo-y-Jos%C3%A9-Batista-Panam%C3%A1-vence-02-a-Martinica|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Murillo started three of Panama's ten [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – CONCACAF fifth round|CONCACAF Hexagonal matches]] in the final round of [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] qualifying,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prosoccerusa.com/world-cup/2018-fifa-world-cup-get-to-know-the-major-league-soccer-players-in-russia/|title=2018 FIFA World Cup: Get to know the Major League Soccer players in Russia}}</ref> helping Panama qualify for its first World Cup. In May 2018 he was named to [[Panama national football team|Panama]]'s final 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/russia-2018-squads-officially-confirmed|title=Russia 2018 squads officially confirmed|publisher=FIFA
}}</ref> Murillo was the starting [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]] in Panama's [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group G|group stage]] losses to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] and [[England national football team|England]]. He received a yellow card in each of the two matches, making him ineligible to play in the team's final group match against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].

